    <main>
      <article about="" typeof="schema:ScholarlyArticle">
        <h1 property="schema:name">Decentralised Linked Research Application</h1>

        <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
          <p>We observe that majority of the academic knowledge is presented as a package ie. binary file formats (like PDF, Word) merging structural, presentational, and behavioural layers, and often disconnected from other knowledge, due to policy, cost, or technical reasons. A side-effect is that, as research communication is still primarily driven by the constraints of the print medium, it makes it challenging for efficient machine-readable coordination on the Web. One open challenge here is the continuous advancement of creating, communicating, and consuming human and machine-accessible information suitable for the Web platform.</p>

          <p>In the earlier sections, we have discussed progress in research, standards, and practices towards different aspects of realising a decentralised information space. Each dataspace can be individually controlled with access controls for participating agents. Different applications can be implemented to operate on the same data, as well as send activities about the interactions about the data. In this section, we specifically discuss a set of requirements for the implementation of a clientside editor for decentralised article publishing, annotations and social interactions.</p>

          <p>More specifically, we will address the following requirements for the research question on <span class="todo">X</span> in context of <a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#degree-of-control">degree of control</a> (as previously discussed in <cite>Decentralised Storage and Interoperable Applications</cite> section):</p>

           <ul>
            <li>Interoperable applications through Linked Data Notifications and Web Annotations.</li>
            <!-- <li>Creating human and machine-interpretable Web resources.</li> -->
            <li>Actors use their preferred WebID in clientside applications.</li>
            <li>Actors use their preferred clientside application to perform HTTP-based read-write operations on their where they have access to.</li>
            <li>Actors switch between applications without having to move or alter the schema of their data.</li>
            <li>Actors relocating data without having to change their preferred application.</li>
            <li>Querying and visualising statistical data from clientside applications.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>Finally, we will discuss the <a href="#dokieli-forces-functions">forces and functions in dokieli</a>.</p>

          <section id="overview-of-web-publishing-platforms" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#overview-of-web-publishing-platforms">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Overview of Web Publishing Platforms</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description" resource="#related-work" typeof="deo:RelatedWork">
              <p>By <q>Web publishing</q>, we include the process of authoring any kind of unit of information for human and machine consumption, linking between documents or data fragments, as well as dissemination of it.</p>

              <p id="cenrtalised-authoring-and-annotation-platforms"><strong>Centralised authoring and annotation platforms</strong>: There is plethora of examples for centralised systems on the Web. Here we have highlight some of the platforms that are commonly known today and discuss their key architectural approaches. <span id="googledocs-medium-mediawiki"><cite><a href="https://docs.google.com/" rel="cito:discusses">Google Docs</a></cite>, <cite><a href="https://medium.com/" rel="cito:discusses">Medium</a></cite>, and <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia" rel="cito:discusses">Wikipedia</a></cite> (running <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MediaWiki" rel="cito:discusses">MediaWiki</a></cite>) are examples of Web applications for collaborative creation and publication of content. These platforms require individual account creation and data storage with respective to their centralised services. They allow multiple participants to annotate and hold discussions around the primary content; users must access their accounts to be notified of updates to conversations, and data from both the main content and related discussion is confined to the service which was used to create it.</span> <span id="wordpress"><cite><a href="https://wordpress.org/" rel="cito:discusses">WordPress</a></cite> is a free and open-source platform for article publication which can be self-hosted on a server controlled by the user. Visitors may sign-in with their WordPress accounts to leave comments on others’ articles, however they are typically stored by the hosting site’s database.</span> <span id="hypothes.is"><cite><a href="https://hypothes.is/" rel="cito:discusses">Hypothes.is</a></cite> makes it possible for users to leave annotations on different types of documents on the Web using a browser plugin or via their proxy server. Annotations may be private or public, and can be threaded to form conversations around a piece of content. Despite allowing the attachment of annotations to resources hosted anywhere, they depend on centralised account creation and storage for the annotations themselves. Hypothes.is is open source, with its own API to discover annotations on its central servers, and may be self-hosted, but currently it is not possible to federate between different instances.</span> <span id="pundit"><cite><a href="http://thepund.it/" rel="cito:discusses">Pundit</a></cite> (<cite><a href="http://ceur-ws.org/Vol-912/paper4.pdf">Pundit: Semantically Structured Annotations forWeb Contents and Digital Libraries</a></cite>, Grassi, 2012) is a set of tools that allow annotations with highlights, comments and semantic annotations. It is similar to Hypothes.is in its architecture and deployment, ie. annotations made through the client application require it to be saved on a <em>dedicated</em> corresponding annotations server.</span></p>

              <p id="decentralised-authoring-and-annotation-platforms"><strong>Decentralised authoring and annotation systems</strong>: <span id="libreoffice-online">Some of the authoring and publishing systems already fulfill some aspects of decentralised systems. <cite><a href="https://github.com/libreoffice/online" rel="cito:discusses">LibreOffice Online</a></cite>'s <cite>Writer</cite>, for example, allows collaborative editing of office documents from the Web browser. Content can be stored under different CMSs in the cloud. The document’s interface consists of image tiles which are sent from the server and rendered in the browser. However, it hardly provides accessibility, rich interlinking and annotations or <a href="structure-of-scholarly-information#separation-of-concerns">separations of concerns</a>.</span> <span id="pandoc-scholar"><cite><a rel="cito:discusses" href="https://github.com/pandoc-scholar/pandoc-scholar">Pandoc Scholar</a></cite> manuscripts to be written in plain Markdown text files, which can be converted into common publication formats, such as PDF, HTML or EPUB, using Pandoc (<a href="https://peerj.com/articles/cs-112/">Formatting Open Science: agilely creating multiple document formats for academic manuscripts with Pandoc Scholar</a>, Krewinkel, 2017)</span> <span id="smallest-federated-wiki">The <cite><a href="http://fed.wiki.org/" rel="cito:discusses">Smallest Federated Wiki</a></cite> pages to be forked and maintain personal copies.</span> <span id="amaya"><cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/Amaya/" rel="cito:discusses">Amaya</a></cite> is a desktop Web editor application, to create and update documents with remote access features, as well as a lightweight browser that was developed by W3C (1996-2012) to provide a framework to test its technologies. Annotations in Amaya can be attached to a Web document or a selected part of the document (without modifying the primary document) and stored locally or on a remote annotation server.</span></p>

              <p>The tools which provide good collaborative editing user-interfaces appear to do so at the expense of data ownership and interoperability; those which promote creation and publication of data in open reusable formats are lacking facilities for linking discourse and conversation to concepts published. Decentralised creations also mean that each author can choose their own semantics eg. their own vocabulary to annotate using the RDF language, and then such decentralised documents can link to each other and their schemas can also be mapped to each other, whereas in centralised platforms this is (if they support semantics at all) often prescribed, either technically enforced, or encouraged by social convention.</p>


              <p>In <cite><a data-versiondate="2018-12-28T11:36:36Z" data-versionurl="https://web.archive.org/web/20181228113636/http://svn.aksw.org/papers/2011/JWS_SemanticContentAuthoring/public.pdf" href="http://svn.aksw.org/papers/2011/JWS_SemanticContentAuthoring/public.pdf">User Interfaces for Semantic Authoring of Textual Content: A Systematic Literature Review</a></cite>, Khalili et al, 2011, provide an analysis on approaches for <q>Semantic Content Authoring</q> (<abbr title="Semantic Content Authoring">SCA</abbr>), which is defined as <q>a tool-supported manual composition process aiming at the creation of semantic documents. With an ontology and a user interface appropriate for the type of content, semantic authoring can be easier than traditional composition of content and the resulting content can be of higher quality.</q> The article proposes a set of <q>quality attributes</q> - as non-functional requirements - to evaluate the performance of SCA systems: usability, customizability, generalizability, collaboration, portability, accessibility, proactivity, automation, evolvability, interoperability, and scalability. Based on the starting point of the authoring process, the authors distinguish the approaches, and generally categorised as <q>bottom-up</q> (lifting unstructured content to a semantic level) or <q>top-down</q> (semantic representations from the beginning requiring users with the knowledge of the domain), and sometimes a hybrid of the two. A survey of tools are presented (in article's Table 3) covering different types of users, expected domain knowledge, and authoring approach. The article also discusses <cite>Research and Technology Challenges</cite> and identifies a gap in addressing <q>accessibility</q>, <q>handling complexity in UIs</q>, <q>formal and systematic methods for user interface evaluation</q>, <q>heuristic evaluation</q>, <q>support of crowdsourcing</q>, UIs for ubiquitous devices.</p>

              <p class="class">We will reuse <cite><a href="#semantic-content-authoring-quality-attributes">Semantic Content Authoring Quality Attributes</a></cite>. Mention #linked-data-notifications-implementations #comparison-of-annotation-applications #comparison-of-accessibility-applications #comparison-of-interoperability-applications #fair-metrics #adoption-of-dokieli</p>
            </div>
          </section>


          <section id="decentralised-linked-notifications-and-annotations" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#decentralised-linked-notifications-and-annotations">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Decentralised Linked Notifications and Annotations</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>The functional and non-functional requirements from the <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/ldp-ucr/">Linked Data Platform Use Cases and Requirements</a></cite> (<abbr title="Linked Data Platform Use Cases and Requirements">LDP-UCR</abbr>) are applicable for authoring, publishing, and sharing content. In order to represent different units of information in social and scholarly communication, Linked Data <a href="structure-of-scholarly-information#vocabularies">vocabularies</a> can be used.</p>

              <p>By using different arrangements of LDN, WA, AP, LDP mechanisms and related vocabularies, scholarly and social activities can be systematically discovered for a variety of use cases. Decentralised notifications and annotations surrounding an article can be determined as follows:</p>

              <ul>
                <li id="subject-annotation-service">Resource asserts the location of a preferred service for maintaining annotations about the the subject resource (via <code>oa:annotationService</code>)</li>
                <li id="subject-inbox">Resource asserts the location of a service that receives and serves notifications about the subject resource (via <code>ldp:inbox</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-storage">An individual's profile asserting their preferred storage location (via <code>pim:storage</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-outbox">An individual's profile asserting the location of their activities (via <code>as:outbox</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-index">An individual's profile asserting their type index registrations (via <code>solid:publicTypeIndex</code>)</li>
                <li id="profile-knows-profile-storage">Members of an individual's social graph (via eg. <code>foaf:knows</code>) asserting their preferred storage location</li>
                <li id="profile-knows-profile-outbox">Members of an individual's social graph asserting the location of their activities</li>
                <li id="profile-knowns-profile-index">Members of an individual's social graph sharing their type index registration (via <code>solid:publicTypeIndex</code>)</li>
                <li id="inbox-annotation-known">Inbox or annotation service locations are known prior to interaction eg. trusted or used by a community.</li>
                <li id="inbox-annotation-manual">Inbox or annotation service locations are manually input to the system eg. not publicised or private.</li>
              </ul>

              <p>Applications can incrementally implement a combination of these approaches to deliver and discover distributed activities on the Web. For example, the preferred locations for general data storage, annotations and notifications for resources can be discovered, and used as input to create new resources eg. assigning an inbox for an annotation where the inbox location is derived from a profile's preferred location for a class of information. Thereby a chain of operations can be orchestrated for decentralised units of information.</p>

              <p>Figure X depicts an interplay of decentralised personal profiles, notifications, and annotations.</p>

              <figure class="todo">
                <figcaption>Interplay of Personal Profiles, Notifications, and Annotations</figcaption>
              </figure>
            </div>
          </section>


          <section id="implementing-a-read-write-application" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#implementing-a-read-write-application">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Implementing a Read-Write Application</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>In this section we demonstrate how the various standards described can be pieced together into an application designed for researchers to participate in the scholarly communication ecosystem autonomously. We highlight some scholarly communication use cases with <cite><a href="https://dokie.li/">dokieli</a></cite>, a clientside editor for decentralised article publishing, annotations and social interactions.</p>

              <p>dokieli implements the use cases pertaining to <a href="#decentralised-linked-notifications-and-annotations">Decentralised Linked Notifications and Annotations</a> as outlined earlier, as well as those specific to <a href="linked-data-notifications#scholarly-communication-notification-use-cases">scholarly communication</a>.</p>

              <p>dokieli is inherently a general-purpose authoring, annotating, and notifying application. While it implements use cases specific to research or scholarly communication, it is not constrained to it. For instance, dokieli is capable of rendering the following use cases from the W3C <cite><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/">RDFa Use Cases: Scenarios for Embedding RDF in HTML</a></cite>: <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-1">Basic Structured Blogging</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-2">Publishing an Event - Overriding Some of the Rendered Data</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-3">Content Management Metadata</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-5">Web Clipboard</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-7">Advanced Data Structures</q>, and <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-8">Augmented Browsing for Scientists</q>, <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-scenarios/#use-case-9">Publishing a RDF Vocabulary</q>.</p>

              <p>dokieli uses LDN to send and consume notifications: When a reader comments on a fragment of text in an article, the application discovers the article’s Inbox and sends a notification about the annotation. dokieli also consumes notifications from this Inbox to fetch and display the annotation as marginalia (<a href="#figure-dokieli-annotation">figure 2</a>). A reader can share a dokieli-enabled article with their contacts; dokieli discovers each contact’s Inbox and sends a notification there (<a href="#figure-dokieli-share">figure 3</a>). When editing an article, the author can add a citation. If an Inbox is discovered in the cited article, dokieli sends a notification there to indicate what part of the article was cited by whom and where. dokieli-enabled articles also consume citation notifications to display these metrics for the author and other readers (<a href="#figure-dokieli-citation">figure 4</a>).</p>


<!--
<pre>
*** outbox in WebID Profile ... discuss in connection to extension
*** memento, immutable.. internet archive features
</pre>
-->


              <p>In this section we describe dokieli's architecture which enables creators of information to:</p>

              <ul>
                <li>use their own WebIDs to identify themselves with, and have their profile information known to application</li>
                <li>self-publish and consume human and machine-interpretable Linked Data, and decide where they can be accessed from</li>
                <li>use a notification system to create awareness, facilitate discovery and reuse</li>
              </ul>

<hr />


              <section id="information-overview" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#information-overview">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Information Overview</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>Here we summarise the key protocols and data models that dokieli uses. Later, we will describe some key use cases in more detail.</p>

                  <p id="separation-of-concerns"><strong>Separation of Concerns</strong>: dokieli adopts <cite>progressive enhancement</cite> strategy for the structural, presentational, and behavioural layers to allow content and base functionality to be accessible through different media and devices. The content representation in HTML+RDFa that dokieli produces is accessible (readable by human and machine consumers) without requiring any CSS or JavaScript, ie. text-browser safe.</p>

                  <p id="human-machine-readable"><strong>Human and Machine-Readable</strong>: <a href="structure-of-scholarly-information#why-rdfa">Why RDFa</a> explained having all human-visible content in HTML, and all structured statements be made in context of their content in RDFa, thereby a close association between structured data and visual locality. dokieli takes this approach when preparing documents, also to avoid any data duplication in the same document - adhering to the <abbr title="Don't Repeat Yourself">DRY</abbr> principle. The approach also helps to avoid the creation and usage of multiple data islands, ie. separately for humans and machines. Consequently, it has the advantage of not having any dependency on JavaScript in order to make the hidden machine-readable content be consumable from a human user interface. One exception to this rule is where dokieli allows authors to use embed Turtle, JSON-LD, or TriG data blocks in HTML typically for the purpose of non-prose information. We cannot know in advance what new kinds of information or data can be integrated into articles. So, dokieli sets no constraints on what information and how it can be be expressed in order to facilitate extensibility. Information can be expressed using different vocabularies, enabling reuse of existing data models and the addition of new semantic expressions.</p>

                  <p id="serialisations"><strong>Serialisations</strong>: dokieli can serialise articles, annotations, and notifications in HTML+RDFa, Turtle, and JSON-LD, depending on server content-negotiation. Articles are represented in HTML+RDFa so that information is usable by both humans and machine consumers while maintaining lowest requirements for publishing, eg. a single URL with full payload in HTML+RDFa can be accessible from any HTTP server. No additional requirements necessary from clients eg. JavaScript support and enabled, or servers eg. additional RDF based content-negotiation. For annotations and notifications, dokieli first meets interoperability requirements (for protocols and vocabularies), and remains flexible about the serialisation that servers prefer. Similarly for consuming content, it can work with any of the serialisations as mentioned.</p>

                  <p id="notification-inbox"><strong>Notification Inbox</strong>: An article or an arbitrary unit of information within may be associated with a notification inbox as per LDN's <code>ldp:inbox</code>. Articles containing the inbox relation is detected by dokieli, and used to send notifications about annotations that the user creates. While orthogonal, articles and inboxes can also preserve context in that a unique inbox can be associated with a unique version of an article, so that annotations will refer to the specific version of an article, as well as being specifically recalled through the unique inbox. dokieli also enables users to assign an inbox for the annotation that they are creating. This has the advantage that the annotation has its own inbox and it can be discovered by other means. This approach is supplementary to threaded annotations, ie. annotations on annotations, can be used independently of the primary article. The assignment of the inbox comes from user's preferred location for an inbox for the purpose of announcements. It is based on Solid's Type Index Registration approach."</p>

                  <p id="annotation-service"><strong>Annotation Service</strong>: Articles can be associated with an annotation service located anywhere on the Web as per WA's <code>oa:annotationService</code>. Articles containing the annotation service relation is detected by dokieli, and offered as an optional location to send annotations to.</p>

                  <p id="license"><strong>License</strong>: Actors can assign any license and rights to their documents or any fragment within. All of the Creative Commons licenses are available from the dokieli UI for actors to use for articles and annotations. Notifications are licensed with CC0 1.0 Universal (public domain dedication).</p>

                  <p>dokieli applies the notion of articles, annotations, notifications, and profiles as described in <a href="structure-of-scholarly-informationunits-of-communication">Units of Communication</a>. Creating articles, annotations, and notifications in dokieli is intended to be done through its UI, and generates the required structured content.</p>

                  <p id="articles"><strong>Articles</strong>: An article - in the most general sense of the term - may contain RDF classes like <code>schema:CreativeWork</code>, <code>sioc:Post</code>, <code>prov:Entity</code>, <code>schema:Article</code>, <code>as:Article</code>. While the body of annotations may also considered as articles in their own right, we reserve the usage of the term articles in particular to primary research documents typically containing structured prose. Actors can assign unique identifiers to any fragment of information.</p>

                  <p id="annotations"><strong>Annotations</strong>: dokieli uses the Web Annotation <cite>Data Model</cite> and <cite>Vocabulary</cite> to express the annotations it creates, as well as implementing the Web Annotation <cite>Protocol</cite> in order to communicate with conforming annotation servers. dokieli applies the <cite>Embedding Web Annotations in HTML</cite> approach. In fact, the examples in the W3C Note were derived from dokieli's application of the WA vocabulary for HTML+RDFa representations. An annotation has the <code>oa:Annotation</code> RDF class, contains a link to its body content and the target resource in which it is associated with. dokieli also uses the WA <cite>Selectors and States</cite> for selecting part of a resource and generating a dereferenceable HTTP URI. Annotations can be done at the document as well as sentence level.</p>

                  <p id="notifications"><strong>Notifications</strong>: dokieli implements the LDN protocol to discover social and scholarly activities, such as annotations with different motivations, as well as sending contextual notifications to recipients (like documents or web-agents). A notification may have one of the following classes: <code>as:Announce</code>, <code>as:Like</code>, <code>as:Dislike</code>, <code>as:Relationship</code>.</p>

                  <p id="profiles"><strong>Profiles</strong>: Actors can use their personal WebIDs, and profile descriptions when interacting with the Web resources.</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="personal-identities" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#personal-identities">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Personal Identities</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p id="authentication"><strong>Authentication</strong>: Actors can authenticate themselves using <a href="#webid-tls">WebID-TLS</a> and <a href="#webid-oidc">WebID-OIDC</a> mechanisms on route to determine their level of authorization to read, write, and control resources. The workflow for authentication starts by user inputting their WebID (HTTP URI) or their Identity Provider URL as a shorthand for their WebID in dokieli UI. The Web resources in which the user wishes to interact with may be under any domain, whether self-hosted or another party's, running a server application conforming to the same standards.</p>

                  <p id="profile-description">In order to adopt dokieli's user-interface and the kinds of interactions that user can perform, we dereference the user's <a href="#webid">WebID</a> (HTTP URI), and parse the <a href="#webid-profile">WebID Profile</a> document to glean the following kinds of information:</p>

                  <ul>
                    <li>Name (eg. <code>foaf:name</code> and equivalents)</li>
                    <li>Image (eg. <code>foaf:image</code> and equivalents)</li>
                    <li>Homepage (eg. <code>foaf:homepage</code> and equivalents)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#social-graph">Social graph</a> (<code>foaf:knows</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#pds">Storage</a> (<code>pim:storage</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="linked-data-notifications#inbox-notification">Inbox</a> (<code>ldp:inbox</code>, and alias <code>as:inbox</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#activitypub">Outbox</a> (<code>as:outbox</code>)</li>
                    <li>Preferences (<code>pim:preferencesFile</code>, <code>solid:publicTypeIndex</code>, <code>solid:privateTypeIndex</code>)</li>
                    <li>Preferred proxy (<code>solid:preferredProxy</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#multiple-identities">Multiple identities</a> (<code>owl:sameAs</code>)</li>
                    <li>Additional information (<code>rdfs:seeAlso</code>)</li>
                    <li><a href="decentralising-scholarly-communication#webid-tls-delegation">Delegated agent</a> (<code>acl:delegates</code>)</li>
                  </ul>

                  <p>When dokieli encounters <code>owl:sameAs</code> and <code>rdfs:seeAlso</code>, 
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="creating-resources" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#creating-resources">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Creating Resources</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">

                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="publishing-resources" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#publishing-resources">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Publishing Resources</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">

                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="annotations" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#annotations">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Annotations</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>Once the annotation is created and has a dereferenceable HTTP URI (subject to access control rules), a notification can be sent to the inbox of the target resource about the annotation if an article or arbitrary parts advertises an LDN inbox. Depending on the motivation of the annotation, the notification is modelled with the Activity vocabulary eg. <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/activitystreams-vocabulary/#dfn-create">Create</a>, to indicate that the actor has created the object.</p>

                  <p>In order to discover and view previously created annotations around article, dokieli follows LDN's discovery mechanism for notifications about annotations, and then subsequently fetches the annotations in order to display them in context of what they are associated with.</p>

                  <p>users have the option to assign a unique inbox to the annotation..</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="social-sharing" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#social-sharing">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Social Sharing</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>The notification is modelled with using of the Activity vocabulary's eg. <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/activitystreams-vocabulary/#dfn-announce">Announce</a>, to indicate that the actor is calling the target's attention the object.</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="dokieli-privacy" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#dokieli-privacy">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Privacy in dokieli</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
                  <p>own personal data storage for articles, annotations, and inbox</p>
                  <p>Preferred proxy</p>
                  <p>activities</p>
                </div>
              </section>

              <section id="interactive-linked-statistics" inlist="" rel="schame:hasPart" resource="#sparqlines">
                <h3 property="schema:name">Interactive Linked Statistics</h3>
                <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
<p><a href="http://csarven.ca/sparqlines-sparql-to-sparkline">http://csarven.ca/sparqlines-sparql-to-sparkline</a></p>
<p>
* write challenges/limitations for something like sparqlines.. eg. remote data.. offline.. archiving/caching..
</p>
                            <p>This article presents <em>sparqlines</em>: statistical observations fetched from SPARQL endpoints and displayed as inline-charts. An inline-chart, also known as a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sparkline"><em>sparkline</em></a>, is concise, and located where it is discussed in the text, complementing the supporting text without breaking the reader’s flow. For example, the 
